are some 8,500 there now -- can

29:56.533 --> 29:59.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
help sustain the current
security stalemate.

29:59.933 --> 30:04.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I don't believe that
troops alone will actually
be decisive in the end.

30:05.800 --> 30:07.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Troops alone can't win this war.

30:07.433 --> 30:10.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Troops alone will not
remove the stalemate.

30:10.866 --> 30:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The stalemate fundamentally
rests on the political
side of the equation.

30:14.733 --> 30:19.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, alongside any
military surge, any --
the addition of any number
of U.S. troops, I will

30:21.800 --> 30:24.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be very interested to hear the
administration's ambitions in
terms of how they're going to

30:25.533 --> 30:27.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
deal with the politics.

30:27.633 --> 30:29.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Well, explain
what the challenges are there
for the politics in Afghanistan.

30:29.566 --> 30:30.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

30:30.566 --> 30:32.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

30:32.466 --> 30:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS LUTE: Well, I look
at this as a three-part
equation on the political side.

30:34.500 --> 30:38.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, first of all, inside the
Afghan government itself, here
you have zero-sum politics among

30:40.366 --> 30:42.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the different national players.

30:42.166 --> 30:44.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have a high
level of corruption.

30:44.033 --> 30:46.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have the patronage network.

30:46.500 --> 30:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have a long period
of time where you have
actually had stalemate
from the central government

30:52.500 --> 30:55.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
itself.

30:55.033 --> 30:58.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Second, you have stalemate
between Afghanistan
and its neighboring
states, most prominently

30:58.466 --> 31:00.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pakistan, but not just Pakistan.

31:00.566 --> 31:05.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We only have to look at the map
and see the geographic equation
here, which includes Iran

31:06.966 --> 31:10.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the west, Central Asia,
and Russia to the north, and
beyond, to the northeast China,

31:14.366 --> 31:15.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and further to the east, India.

31:15.900 --> 31:20.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So this is a very complex
regional diplomatic equation.

31:20.366 --> 31:24.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All those players I have just
mention have some impact on
what happens inside Afghanistan.

31:24.633 --> 31:29.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then, ultimately,
to bring this war to a
conclusion, a political
end, which the military

31:31.566 --> 31:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
equation should be in support
of, it involves politics between
the Afghan government and

31:36.300 --> 31:38.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Taliban, the opponent.

31:38.800 --> 31:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so on all three of
these fronts, inside
Kabul, in the region, and
between the government

31:42.500 --> 31:45.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the insurgents, there's a
real need for a political surge.

31:45.800 --> 31:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Among those
neighbors, Pakistan obviously
looms very large in Afghanistan,

31:49.966 --> 31:54.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and provide a consistent safe
haven for the Taliban that are
waging this massive insurgency

31:54.866 --> 31:56.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the country.

31:56.366 --> 32:00.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How can the U.S. get Pakistan
to help us in that fight?

32:00.666 --> 32:01.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

32:01.633 --> 32:03.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

32:03.733 --> 32:05.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS LUTE: Well, first of
all, I think you have to place
our requirements, our demands

32:05.900 --> 32:10.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on Pakistan in this part of
the arena, that is, their
support for the Taliban, in the

32:12.300 --> 32:14.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
context of our other
interests in Pakistan.

32:14.966 --> 32:19.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we actually have several
interests in Pakistan which
I think surpass our interest

32:21.100 --> 32:22.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in dealing with
the Afghan Taliban.

32:22.600 --> 32:26.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I would label Pakistan's
internal stability itself.

32:26.766 --> 32:31.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Here you have more than
180 million Pakistanis
in a country where you
have not just the Afghan

32:33.733 --> 32:38.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Taliban, but the Pakistani
Taliban, remnants of al-Qaida,
and other regional terrorist

32:39.933 --> 32:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
groups, all of which threaten
the stability of the state.

32:41.166 --> 32:42.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A
nuclear-powered state.

32:42.366 --> 32:43.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

32:43.366 --> 32:45.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

32:45.933 --> 32:47.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS LUTE: And a state
which has the fastest
growing, the fastest
expanding nuclear arsenal

32:47.633 --> 32:49.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the world.

32:49.700 --> 32:53.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that very dangerous cocktail
of terrorists, extremists, and
nuclear weapons is actually

32:55.933 --> 33:00.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
probably more of a
vital national interest
to us than Pakistan's
support for the Afghan

33:01.433 --> 33:03.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Taliban.

33:03.433 --> 33:06.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there's a large array
of complex interests
here which are at play.

33:06.066 --> 33:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Even if the
administration articulates a
strategy, do you think that

33:09.433 --> 33:11.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this administration can
execute that strategy?

33:11.833 --> 33:12.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

33:12.833 --> 33:14.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

33:14.866 --> 33:16.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS LUTE: Well, I
think, right now, they're
working with a handicap.

33:16.933 --> 33:20.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is, while the National
Security Council itself, those
who set strategy and overwatch

33:22.866 --> 33:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the strategy, is largely
in place, the implementers
of the strategy are
largely not in place,

33:28.066 --> 33:31.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because they have a
large number of vacancies
among those officials who
are yet to be nominated

33:31.166 --> 33:34.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and confirmed by the
Senate, especially in
the Defense Department
and the State Department.

33:34.933 --> 33:39.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Former
Ambassador Douglas Lute,
thank you very much.

33:41.966 --> 33:43.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

33:43.033 --> 33:44.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

33:44.100 --> 33:48.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DOUGLAS LUTE: Thank you.

33:48.400 --> 33:53.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The future
of coal is very much at the
center of debate right now when

33:54.600 --> 33:57.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it comes to the politics
and business of energy.

33:57.800 --> 34:02.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Whatever you may think about
those questions, the U.S.
still uses a lot of coal.

34:02.766 --> 34:07.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About 30 percent of our
energy, of our electricity
is generated by it.

34:07.233 --> 34:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For some, the Holy Grail is
new technology that captures
some of coal's worst problems

34:12.966 --> 34:15.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with greenhouse gases.

34:15.266 --> 34:18.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien reports
on the largest facility
trying to do so.

34:18.966 --> 34:23.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of our weekly
series on the Leading Edge
of science and technology.

34:23.133 --> 34:28.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: At the
W.A. Parish power plant
southwest of Houston,
they are piling up coal,

34:30.133 --> 34:34.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
getting ready for another
long, hot, aggressively
air-conditioned summer.

34:36.733 --> 34:39.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the largest fossil fuel
power plants in the country,
Parish can generate about

34:39.566 --> 34:44.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
one-fifth of the city's
electricity using coal-
and gas-fired turbines.

34:46.233 --> 34:50.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And it is leading the
nation down a promising,
yet problematic path.

34:50.933 --> 34:55.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Here, they are trying
to make clean coal more
than a political slogan.

34:57.366 --> 35:01.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mauricio Gutierrez is CEO
of NRG, owner of the plant.

35:03.466 --> 35:04.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAURICIO GUTIERREZ, President
and CEO, NRG: We built the
world's largest carbon capture

35:04.766 --> 35:08.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
system on an existing
coal-fired power plant.

35:08.866 --> 35:12.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is the first commercial
scale facility of this
kind in the United States.

35:12.633 --> 35:17.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: They are
capturing and storing
carbon dioxide, the
greenhouse gas that is

35:18.800 --> 35:21.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the main driver
of global warming.

35:21.033 --> 35:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is prompting some
unexpected support from members
of the Trump administration.

35:25.733 --> 35:29.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Listen to Energy Secretary
Rick Perry at the ceremonial
opening in April.

35:29.566 --> 35:33.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK PERRY, U.S. Secretary of
Energy: I think the solutions
to many of the challenges that

35:33.200 --> 35:38.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have in the world today
are displayed behind me.

35:40.166 --> 35:43.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The same Rick
Perry who wrote a book calling
climate scientists members

35:43.066 --> 35:48.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a secular carbon cult who
manipulate data and climate
science a contrived, phony mess,

35:50.300 --> 35:52.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
but not here.

35:52.366 --> 35:56.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK PERRY: It shows we don't
have to pit the environment
on one side weighing and the

35:57.433 --> 36:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
economy on the other side.

36:00.200 --> 36:04.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We can and we will be
good stewards of both.

36:04.733 --> 36:09.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The steward of
this project for NRG is David
Greeson, the vice president

36:10.600 --> 36:12.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of development.

36:12.600 --> 36:14.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID GREESON, Vice President
of Development, NRG: We're
interested in doing more carbon

36:14.566 --> 36:19.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
capture as a part of our overall
sustainable energy future
plan, and so we're going to

36:20.533 --> 36:22.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
see how this one works.

36:22.633 --> 36:26.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They call the
billion-dollar carbon capture
and storage system Petra Nova.

36:28.600 --> 36:32.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NRG built it in partnership
with the Japanese oil company
JX Nippon using a $190 million

36:34.833 --> 36:39.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
grant from the Department
of Energy doled out during
the Obama administration.

36:39.033 --> 36:44.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DAVID GREESON: So we're
capturing about 200
tons of CO2 per hour.

36:45.933 --> 36:50.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
On an annual basis, that's
about 1.6 million tons per year.

36:50.333 --> 36:54.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the equivalent of 350,000
cars being taken off the road.

36:54.666 --> 36:59.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: While it may
be the world's largest carbon
capture facility, it is still

36:59.166 --> 37:04.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
only removing about 10 percent
of the CO2 created by the
four coal-fired generators

37:04.933 --> 37:06.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
here.

37:06.133 --> 37:08.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The only obstacle to
capturing more is money.

37:08.766 --> 37:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID GREESON: We're just now
reaching the point where this
technology is mature enough

37:13.133 --> 37:18.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be considered for rollout
to the broad coal-fired fleet
in the United States and

37:20.300 --> 37:21.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
around the world.

37:21.466 --> 37:23.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN:
Here's how it works.

37:23.566 --> 37:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Flue gas, with carbon dioxide
in it, flows through a duct to
the carbon capture facility.

37:30.166 --> 37:34.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
One vessel contains
amine, an ammonia-based
chemical in liquid form.

37:35.600 --> 37:37.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It naturally binds
with carbon dioxide.

37:37.866 --> 37:42.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With the carbon now in solution,
the liquid goes to another
vessel, where it is heated

37:42.566 --> 37:44.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

37:44.566 --> 37:48.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As that happens, the
process is reversed and
the CO2 pops out as a gas.

37:50.566 --> 37:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is captured, and, after
it is compressed, ready
for underground storage.

37:54.233 --> 37:56.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL WEBBERMD-B,
University of Texas at Austin:
I think Petra Nova is a shining

37:56.700 --> 38:00.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
example of what technology
offers, and so, as an engineer,
I'm very enthusiastic about

38:00.966 --> 38:01.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

38:01.966 --> 38:04.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think it's very exciting.

38:04.000 --> 38:06.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Michael Webber
is deputy director of the Energy
Institute at the University

38:06.633 --> 38:08.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Texas at Austin.

38:08.466 --> 38:12.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He says the energy
sector is watching this
project very closely.

38:12.766 --> 38:16.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL WEBBER: We're getting a
lot of scrutiny because people
want to know if carbon capture

38:16.633 --> 38:18.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and sequestration will work.

38:18.700 --> 38:21.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there are examples around
the nation, around the world
where it hasn't really quite

38:21.133 --> 38:23.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
come together the
way people want.

38:23.166 --> 38:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's really expensive and hard
to do, so you wouldn't do it
unless you had to, or it's

38:26.233 --> 38:28.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in your economic favor to do so.

38:28.166 --> 38:32.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And a
coincidence of geography
has made that possible here.

38:32.333 --> 38:37.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The CO2 from the Petra Nova
facility is sent 80 miles to
the southwest, to the West Ranch

38:38.700 --> 38:40.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
oil field.

38:40.233 --> 38:44.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Here, the gas is as good as
gold, black gold, Texas tea.

38:44.733 --> 38:48.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JILL FISK, Senior Vice
President, Hilcorp: That
was the hope, if you
marry up a partnership

38:48.733 --> 38:53.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
between a CO2 emitter where
they can capture the CO2 and
reduce their CO2 emissions, but

38:55.166 --> 38:59.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
then that CO2 can be used
to increase oil production.

39:00.633 --> 39:02.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's really a win-win.

39:02.700 --> 39:05.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Jill Fisk is
a senior vice president for
Hilcorp, the current operator

39:05.733 --> 39:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of this oil field, which
first opened in the 1930s.

39:10.000 --> 39:14.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
At its peak in the
'70s, it produced 50,000
barrels of oil a day.

39:14.700 --> 39:18.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Today, it's down to less
than 300 barrels a day.

39:18.400 --> 39:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Normally, it would be time
to cap the wells here.

39:21.800 --> 39:26.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, instead, they're drilling
new ones, getting ready to pump
a lot more oil by injecting

39:27.666 --> 39:30.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
carbon dioxide deep underground.

39:30.333 --> 39:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Liquid CO2 has been used to
liberate the most stubborn
oil for about 40 years.

39:37.366 --> 39:40.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JILL FISK: Essentially, what's
happening is the oil is stuck
to rock, if you can imagine

39:40.833 --> 39:42.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

39:42.866 --> 39:46.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The CO2 is injected,
it dissolves into that
oil that's stuck to the
rock, loosens up the

39:48.800 --> 39:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
oil, lightens it up, which --
so it can then flow toward a
producer and produce additional

39:52.566 --> 39:54.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
oil.

39:54.633 --> 39:57.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At West Ranch, we're expecting
to recover an additional 60
million barrels of oil that

39:57.766 --> 40:01.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would otherwise be left in the
ground and be unrecoverable
without a project of this

40:01.800 --> 40:03.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
type.

40:03.833 --> 40:07.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Right now,
with oil prices so low, Petra
Nova is breaking even, but,

40:07.733 --> 40:12.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over the next decade, they
expect to make a tidy profit
capturing and burying carbon

40:12.466 --> 40:14.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
dioxide.

40:14.500 --> 40:19.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But doesn't this just transfer
greenhouse gas emissions
from a power plant smokestack

40:19.133 --> 40:21.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to automobile tailpipes?

40:21.233 --> 40:25.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JILL FISK: So, I think that
demand for oil is either going
to be met by foreign oil that

40:27.500 --> 40:31.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the United States has
to purchase or by our
own production that
we're able to supply.

40:31.033 --> 40:36.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So this project is breathing
new life into a field in the
U.S. to help supply that demand

40:36.533 --> 40:38.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for oil.

40:38.600 --> 40:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But how
can we be certain buried
CO2 will stay underground?

40:44.566 --> 40:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Scientists from the University
of Texas are running tests at
22 monitoring wells at West

40:48.366 --> 40:53.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ranch, getting baseline data
so they will know later if
the injected CO2 triggers some

40:55.366 --> 40:59.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
unintended consequences, like
earthquakes or the release
of deep dwelling salt water,

41:00.666 --> 41:02.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
minerals, or chemicals.

41:02.900 --> 41:07.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At this test site in Austin,
they are finding new ways
to monitor the buried CO2.

41:07.733 --> 41:10.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SUE HOVORKA, University of Texas
at Austin: You ready to start?

41:10.266 --> 41:13.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: They pump
the gas into groundwater
to simulate leaks.

41:13.700 --> 41:16.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They use a sensor
that measures light.

41:16.666 --> 41:21.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is coated with a polymer that
thins when it reacts with CO2.

41:21.333 --> 41:26.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If there's any trouble,
the sensor detects more
light, and an alarm is
transmitted automatically.

41:27.833 --> 41:30.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Geologist Sue Hovorka
leads this effort.

41:30.166 --> 41:34.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUE HOVORKA: We need to get
good enough to provide value
to the atmosphere, and we need

41:34.166 --> 41:36.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to avoid unacceptable
consequences.

41:36.433 --> 41:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Hovorka analyzes
deep rock core samples stored
in a cavernous warehouse

41:42.800 --> 41:45.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the Bureau of Economic
Geology in Austin.

41:45.766 --> 41:50.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She says there are ample places
to bury carbon dioxide produced
by all types of fossil fuel

41:52.000 --> 41:54.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
power plants, not
just coal burners.

41:54.333 --> 41:58.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That would be a
monumental step toward
addressing climate change.

41:58.066 --> 42:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUE HOVORKA: If consumers want
to use coal and want to reduce
the carbon from that, the

42:02.733 --> 42:04.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
system to do that
is ready to go.

42:04.300 --> 42:06.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have to pay for it.

42:06.266 --> 42:08.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not outrageous.

42:08.233 --> 42:10.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's totally possible,
but it's not free.

42:10.366 --> 42:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Up until now,
clean coal has been nothing
more than a marketing myth.

42:17.066 --> 42:20.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It could become a reality at
no small cost, but at a small
fraction of the toll if the

42:21.833 --> 42:25.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
industry does nothing
to stop global warming.

42:25.033 --> 42:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In Richmond, Texas, I'm Miles
O'Brien for the "PBS NewsHour."

42:28.033 --> 42:33.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And as Miles
just said, costs are just one
of the questions about whether

42:34.166 --> 42:36.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this model could be
replicated more widely.

42:36.566 --> 42:38.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And Miles joins me
now from Boston.

42:38.933 --> 42:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Miles, tell us more
about why -- and so this is
the first plant of its kind.

42:43.400 --> 42:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What are the challenges
in trying to replicate
this somewhere else and
getting the same results?

42:50.433 --> 42:54.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well,
Judy, the secret sauce
of this one, according
to the innovators behind

42:55.533 --> 42:59.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it, is, they reduced the cost
of creating the carbon capture.

43:01.300 --> 43:04.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
When I say cost,
the cost in power.

43:04.100 --> 43:09.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Normally, what the assumption
is, that it reduces the output
of any given power plant

43:10.666 --> 43:14.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
by as much as 30 percent
in order to run the
carbon capture system.

43:14.333 --> 43:19.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What they did in this case was
they decided not to use the
actual turbines which light

43:21.800 --> 43:24.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the lights that I'm using
right now, but rather a
separate co-generation
plant air, a smaller

43:25.833 --> 43:27.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
power plant on site that can
be run much more efficiently.

43:27.900 --> 43:32.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they say that they -- it's
costing them about 15 percent
of the power-generating capacity

43:33.933 --> 43:35.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of that plant.

43:35.366 --> 43:37.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So that's a big hurdle
that they have gotten over.

43:37.366 --> 43:41.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, 15 percent is still a
big number, and unless you
have some commodity or the CO2

43:43.100 --> 43:46.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has some value, the business
model doesn't add up just yet.

43:46.800 --> 43:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you were
telling us, Miles, there are
also some physical challenges as

43:51.333 --> 43:53.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
well.

43:53.400 --> 43:57.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, being 80
miles near an old oil field that
could use that CO2 to capture

43:59.266 --> 44:01.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and recover a lot of
stubborn oil from the
ground makes it all work.

44:01.700 --> 44:05.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question is, could a
fossil fuel plant of any kind
that's a long way away from an

44:05.600 --> 44:10.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
oil field, could it avail itself
of this kind of transaction?

44:10.600 --> 44:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And CO2 can be pumped in
pipelines for an indefinite
amount of distance, as long as

44:17.166 --> 44:20.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
you recompress every now
and then, sort of have
a booster system in.

44:20.166 --> 44:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, again, that's going
to be a significant cost.

44:23.200 --> 44:27.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is not an insurmountable
thing technologically,
and it could be done.

44:27.366 --> 44:31.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We already have significant CO2
pipelines in the oil sector.

44:31.666 --> 44:34.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You could extend it out, if
you were determined to do this.

44:34.166 --> 44:38.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, just
quickly, you were also saying
other practical limits.

44:38.033 --> 44:40.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, yes.

44:40.200 --> 44:45.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's -- the limits on this are
-- there are some concerns,
for example, about putting

44:46.566 --> 44:49.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CO2 in seismically active
places, for example.

44:49.466 --> 44:53.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You wouldn't want to put
buried CO2 underneath San
Francisco, for example.

44:53.966 --> 44:58.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, having said all that, when
you consider all the places
that it can be stored, the

45:01.033 --> 45:03.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
